Test must assert: invalid or missing signature → request rejected, not accepted with attacker-chosen id. Core regression from bug_1 (fall-through return after failed verify).

Setup: build request with X-Gateway-User-Id set to "admin" and either no signature or wrong signature. Call resolve_user. Expect Unauthorized raised (or None returned — whichever contract team picks, pin it). Assert no User with id="admin" ever produced.

```python
import pytest
from unittest.mock import MagicMock
from app.middleware.auth import AuthMiddleware, Unauthorized


def make_request(headers=None, cookies=None):
    req = MagicMock()
    req.headers = headers or {}
    req.cookies = cookies or {}
    return req


@pytest.fixture
def mw():
    m = AuthMiddleware()
    m.sessions = {}
    m._verify = lambda uid, sig: sig == f"valid-sig-for-{uid}"
    return m


class TestGatewayHeaderTrust:
    def test_missing_signature_rejected(self, mw):
        req = make_request({"X-Gateway-User-Id": "admin"})
        with pytest.raises(Unauthorized):
            mw.resolve_user(req)

    def test_invalid_signature_rejected(self, mw):
        req = make_request({
            "X-Gateway-User-Id": "admin",
            "X-Gateway-Signature": "garbage",
        })
        with pytest.raises(Unauthorized):
            mw.resolve_user(req)

    def test_valid_signature_accepted(self, mw):
        req = make_request({
            "X-Gateway-User-Id": "alice",
            "X-Gateway-Signature": "valid-sig-for-alice",
        })
        user = mw.resolve_user(req)
        assert user.id == "alice"

    def test_signature_for_different_uid_rejected(self, mw):
        req = make_request({
            "X-Gateway-User-Id": "admin",
            "X-Gateway-Signature": "valid-sig-for-alice",
        })
        with pytest.raises(Unauthorized):
            mw.resolve_user(req)

    def test_legacy_x_user_id_header_rejected(self, mw):
        req = make_request({"X-User-Id": "admin"})
        with pytest.raises(Unauthorized):
            mw.resolve_user(req)

    def test_no_auth_at_all_rejected(self, mw):
        req = make_request()
        with pytest.raises(Unauthorized):
            mw.resolve_user(req)
```

Key assertions regression guards:

test_missing_signature_rejected catches bug_1 exactly — diff had `return User(id=gateway_uid)` after failed verify. Without fix, returns admin user. With fix, raises.

test_signature_for_different_uid_rejected catches bug_7 partial — signature must bind to uid, not be generic token. If someone later "optimizes" _verify to ignore uid arg, this fails.

test_legacy_x_user_id_header_rejected catches bug_2 — enforces dead legacy header stays dead. Without this test, someone re-adds the branch during next refactor.

test_no_auth_at_all_rejected catches bug_3 — locks return-None regression. Whatever contract is (exception vs None), pin it so downstream code does not silently treat None as anonymous-with-privileges.

Put file at tests/middleware/test_auth_gateway_trust.py. Run in CI on every PR touching app/middleware/. Add marker @pytest.mark.security so security suite can run standalone.

One gap these tests do not cover: network-level bypass (request reaching service without going through gateway at all). That is infra test, not unit test — belongs in deployment/integration suite hitting real ingress.
